Female":"1203–Deceased","Cir 1225":"1225","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1241":"1241","Abt 1247":"about 1247","1270":"1270","Abt 1241":"about 1241","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","Abt 1243":"about 1243","1243":"1243","1254":"1254","1208":"1208","Zúñiga, Zúñiga, Navarra, España":"Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Spain","Henestrosa, Spain":"Spain",",,, Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ortiz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Carlos, Luis, Manuel, Francisco, Jesus, Miguel, Angel, Jorge, Pedro, Ramon.","Spanish: patronymic from the Basque personal name <i>Orti</i>, from Latin <i>Fortunius</i> (see   Fortuno  ). Compare   Urtiz  .","History: Nicolas Ortiz Ladron de Guevara, a native of Mexico City, came to Santa Fe, NM, in June 1694 with his wife and children and other families recruited to recolonize New Mexico after the Pueblo Indian revolt."],"variants":[{"name":"Fortuno","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Fortuño</b>): from the personal name <i>Fortuño</i>, from Latin <i>Fortunius</i>, derived from <i>fortuna</i> ‘luck’."]},{"name":"Orquiz","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico): perhaps an altered form of Spanish   Ortiz  ."]},{"name":"Ortis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Agustin, Ana, Arturo, Baldomero, Bicente, Consuelo, Emiliano, Ernestina, Gerardo, Jesus, Luis Enrique.","Spanish: variant of   Ortiz  ."]},{"name":"Ortez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Ana, Carlos, Margarita, Mario, Sergio, Adela, Adriana, Amando, Aminta, Andres.","Spanish: variant of   Ortiz   or of Catalan <b>Ortes</b>, plural form of   Orta  ."]},{"name":"Urtiz","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico): altered form of Spanish   Ortiz  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Zúñiga","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Luis, Carlos, Jesus, Jorge, Miguel, Pedro, Alberto, Francisco, Javier.","Basque (<b>Zuñiga</b>, Castilianized as <b>Zúñiga</b>): habitational name from a place in Navarre named Zuñiga (in Castilian: Zúñiga), from Basque <i>zuin</i> ‘cultivated field’ + <i>iga</i> ‘incline, slope’. Compare   Suniga  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Suniga","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Juan, Jose, Raul, Ruben, Xavier, Abelardo, Agapito, Alberto, Ana, Anselma, Benito, Domingo.","Hispanic (also <b>Súñiga</b>): altered form of Basque <b>Zúñiga</b> (see   Zuniga  ). This surname is also found in the Philippines (compare   Sunga  )."]},{"name":"Sunga","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ramon, Jose, Luis, Orlando, Roberto, Amado, Augusto, Eduardo, Eloisa, Elvira, Erlinda, Ernesto.","Hispanic (Philippines; also <b>Suñga</b>): altered form of Basque <b>Zúñiga</b> (see   Zuniga  ). Compare   Suniga  ."]}]},{"name":"Rada","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Delfin, Ernesto, Jose, Lilia, Adelardo, Alipio, Arquimedes, Arturo, Cesar, Cruz, Eladia.","Czech and Slovak: from a short form of any of various Slavic personal names containing the element <i>rad</i> ‘merry, glad’ (from Old Slavic <i>radъ</i>), such as <i>Radoslav</i>, in which the second element means ‘glory’ or ‘famous’.","Hungarian: from the old personal name <i>Rada</i> or <i>Ráda</i>, of Slavic origin (see 1 above and   Rad  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rach","meanings":["German: from Middle High German <i>rach</i> ‘rough, stiff’, a nickname for someone affected by hard work, or a topographic name from the same word in the sense ‘steep, rough’.","Czech, Polish, and Sorbian: from a pet form of the personal names beginning with <i>Ra-</i>, especially Slavic names such as Czech <i>Radoslav</i>, Polish and Sorbian <i>Radosław</i> (see   Rada  )."]},{"name":"Radach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Christoph, Otto, Waltraut.","German: from a short form of any of various Slavic personal names based on Old Slavic <i>radъ</i> ‘merry, glad’ (see   Rada   1).","Americanized form of Czech <b>Radáč</b>: from a pet form of a personal name containing the Slavic element <i>rad</i> ‘merry, glad’ (see   Rada   1)."]},{"name":"Rad","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Ali, Bijan, Abbas, Amad, Masoud, Nader, Nasser, Saeed, Ahmad, Alireza, Amir, Azin.","Iranian: from Persian <i>rād</i> ‘bold, brave’, also ‘skilful, learned’, forming the second part (originally a suffix) of compound names such as <b>Mahdavirad</b> or <b>Mahdavi Rad</b> (see   Mahdavi  ). The surname may also be from the personal name <i>Rād</i>, based on the same word. Compare   Raad   2.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>rād</i>, <i>rāt</i> ‘advice, counsel’."]},{"name":"Radack","meanings":["German: from a Germanized pet form of any of various Slavic personal names based on Old Slavic <i>radъ</i> ‘merry, glad’ (see   Rada   1, compare   Radak  ).","Americanized form of Serbian and Croatian   Radak  .","History: The progenitor of many of the American Radacks was Ephraim Radack, a German from Alt Danzig in the Russian Empire (today Karlivka in Ukraine), a settlement founded by the colonists from Danzig in Prussia (today Gdansk in Poland). He and his family immigrated to SD in the 1870s."]}]},{"name":"María","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Maria  , of German origin but now also moderately popular in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Maria","meanings":["Short form of   Maria  , of German origin but now also moderately popular in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When María Ortiz de Zúñiga Rada was born in 1225, in Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Spain, her father, Ortún Ortíz de Zúñiga Fernandez, was 22 and her mother, Teresa Rada De Beaumont, was 22. She married Pedro Ruiz de Henestrosa in 1235, in Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Spain. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She was buried in Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Spain."},"et":{"Cir 1225–":"1225–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1208–1315":"1208–1315","1245–1315":"1245–1315","1254–Male":"1254–Surnud","1220–1252":"1220–1252","1241–Male":"1241–Surnud","1243–Female":"1243–Surnud","1247–Female":"1247–Surnud","1248–1300":"1248–1300","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1203–1270":"1203–1270","1203–Female":"1203–Surnud","Cir 1225":"1225","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1241":"1241","Abt 1247":"umbes 1247","1270":"1270","Abt 1241":"umbes 1241","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","Abt 1243":"umbes 1243","1243":"1243","1254":"1254","1208":"1208","Zúñiga, Zúñiga, Navarra, España":"Zúñiga, Zuñiga, Nafarroa, Hispaania","Henestrosa, Spain":"Hispaania",",,, Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"Cir 1225–":"1225–Kuollut","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","1208–1315":"1208–1315","1245–1315":"1245–1315","1254–Male":"1254–Kuollut","1220–1252":"1220–1252","1241–Male":"12